VEP 0015
defaultWritten Submission by the Electoral Management Board for Scotland VEP 0015default&#xa0;defaultINTRODUCTIONdefault&#xa0;defaultThis paper provides a set of responses from the Electoral Management Board for Scotland to a series of questions posed by Joint Committee on the draft Voting Eligibility (Prisoners) Bill.  These answers are made by the Convener of the EMB, on the basis of consultation with the Board members an advisers which includes representation from the major professional associations responsible for the delivery of elections in Scotland: solace (Scotland), SOLAR, AEA (Scotland and Northern Ireland Branch) and the Scottish Assessors’ Association.
default&#xa0;
defaultTHE ELECTORAL MANAGEMENT BOARD FOR SCOTLAND default&#xa0;defaultThe Electoral Management Board for Scotland (EMB) was created by the Local Electoral Administration (Scotland) Act 2011, which gave the Board “the general function of co-ordinating the administration of local government elections in Scotland.”  This involves two specific roles:  
default&#xa0;
default(a) assisting local authorities and other persons in carrying out their functions in relation to local government elections; and -
default(b) promoting best practice in local government elections by providing information, advice or training (or otherwise)
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Board is composed of 8 members, 5 of whom are Returning Officers (or their Deputes) and 3 of whom are Electoral Registration Officers.  These are appointed by a Convener who is in turn appointed by Scottish Ministers, through a process of open competition.  Advisors from the professional associations working in electoral administration, SOLAR and the AEA, also attend the Board meetings.  The Electoral Commission, the Scottish Government, Scotland Office and COSLA also have representatives at Board meetings acting as official advisors to provide support and advice.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe EMB’s prime focus is ensuring that the interests of the voter are kept at the centre of all elections planning and administration.  The Board makes much use of the close community of electoral professionals in Scotland to operate by consensus wherever possible.  However, the Convener also has the power to issue directions to Returning Officers and Electoral Registration Officers in relation to their duties around local government elections.  
default&#xa0;
defaultThe local government elections of May 2012 were undertaken with the oversight and coordination of the EMB.  Overall this was a set of elections which were well-run and in which the elector can have full confidence in the results.  There were none of the issues that were faced in 2007 around ballot paper printing or the eCounting systems.  Feedback from all stakeholders indicated that the EMB played a major role in ensuring that this successful outcome was achieved.  The same stakeholders have expressed their appreciation of the work of the EMB and look for its support and coordination to be maintained and developed in future electoral events.
defaultGENERAL COMMENTdefault&#xa0;defaultThe EMB represents those respo
defaultnsible for delivering elections in line with the relevant legislation.  As such we do not intend to comment on the more philosophical issues associated with the franchise or the historic approach to it being withheld from prisoners for example due to the concept of civic death.  Rather in this paper a number of comments are offered on the 
defaultpracticaldefault issues that may arise in the consideration of the extension of the franchise to prisoners.
defaultOnly those questions on which it is appropriate for us to offer a response have been addressed.
default&#xa0;
defaultTHE DRAFT BILLdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe Joint Committee is particularly interested in receiving evidence on the three options for changes to the law set out in the draft bill. They are:default&#xa0;defaulta. Disqualifying prisoners sentenced to 4 years or more in prison from voting.defaultb.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default Disqualifying prisoners sentenced more than 6 months in prison from voting.defaultc.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default Disqualifying all prisoners serving custodial sentences from voting – a restatement of the existing ban.default&#xa0;default default&#xa0;defaultPlease state your opinion on all or any of these options giving clear reasons as to why you, or your organisation, hold that particular view.default&#xa0;default defaultThe Joint Committee would also welcome evidence on whether approaches beyond these options should also be considered.default&#xa0;defaultEMB commentdefault&#xa0;
defaultWe have no preference for whether prisoners should be disenfranchised or not, or which term of imprisonment is most appropriate as a default
default&#xa0;
default It is however important that clear notification is given to the ERO when the prisoner is sentenced and then again when the prisoner is released. It is very common for a prisoner to be sentenced for a certain period of time and only serve a portion of that time. The sentence for instance could be greater than 4 years but the time served could be much less than the 4 years.
default&#xa0;
