default6.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default What would be the likely legal consequences, both domestically and internationally of:default&#xa0;defaulta) keeping the law as it is? defaultb) passing legislation giving some prisoners the right to vote, but in a way that maintains a form of blanket restriction?defaultc) seeking to comply by enfranchising the minimum number of prisoners possible consistent with our international legal obligations?default&#xa0;default7.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default Would giving prisoners the right to vote have any significant administrative impact on either the prison system or the Electoral Commission?default&#xa0;defaultEMB commentdefaultThe 
defaultElectoral 
defaultCommission has no direct role in registering voters. 
default 
defaultPerhaps what is being asked 
defaulthere 
defaultis the effect on Electoral Registration Officers
default (EROs)
default? 
default&#xa0;
defaultIf so 
defaultagain we have no preference for which default system is in place. In 
defaultpracticaldefault terms, however, it would be preferable that the prisoner’s local ERO receives notification from the prison that the person has now been disenfranchised for a specified time or until released from detention whichever is earlier. The alternative to this is that the ERO will have to remain constantly aware or be informed of court proceedings (not necessarily local courts) and remove convicted electors based on legislative rules.  
default&#xa0;
defaultCurrently 
defaultEROs
default are not always informed that a person is now disenfranchised and we rely on normal canvass procedures to identify that someone is no longer resident at an address because they are in prison. Once we know this at present the person is removed from the register.  
defaultIf only some convicted prisoners are disenfranchised, w
defaultithout information from some source such as the prison authorities or the sentencing court we would be unable to distinguish whether a prisoner was disenfranchised or not.
default&#xa0;
default8.default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default Is there any evidence to suggest that allowing prisoners to vote would have a significant impact on particular constituencies? default&#xa0;defaultEMB commentdefaultAs prisons may be relatively large populations in a particular local government ward it would seem sensible to spread that population among a wider area by restriction to previous, or next intended address and only in exceptional circumstances allowing local connection to the prison. However, particularly for longer term prisoners of 2 or more years, the connection with a previous address may become quite tenuous and should perhaps be treated in the same way as overseas voters.  Allowing “local connection” to a future address will also involve a change to the legislation defining local connection and care should be taken to avoid giving rise to a series of competing residences for prisoners. Even if it does not raise the possibility of multiple registrations, this could potentially allow a prisoner to choose where to register. 
default&#xa0;
defaultAllowing registration only at a prison address will mean that the prisoner will always be recorded as having been at that address in that year. This would appear to conflict with the rehabilitation principles of prisoner registration. The requirement to disclose a conviction may have expired but the person’s name could still be found at a prison address by those entitled to use the registers. 
